paragraphs.title: Lets add new column using UDF in Scala
paragraphs.text:
def binarize(s: Int): Int = s match {case 2 => 0 case 4 => 1 }

spark.udf.register("udfValueToCategory", (arg: Int) => binarize(arg)) //In spark 2.3 in pyspark use vector pandas udf

val sqlUDF = spark.sql("SELECT *, udfValueToCategory(clas) from cancerTable")
sqlUDF.show(5)

paragraphs.text:
%md

## Spark Concepts

RDDs are Spark's primary distributed Dataset abstraction. It is a collection of data that is immutable, distributed, lazily evaluated, type inferred, and cacheable. Prior to execution, the developer code (using higher-level constructs such as SQL, DataFrames, and Dataset APIs) is converted to a DAG of RDDs (ready for execution).

Plus: Direct control in pure function , minus: No automatic performance optimisation, requires lot of knowledge on execution on developer 
Spark sql added an automatic optimizer, and spark 2.0 added extra performance using tungsten.
Also used dataset you can use both dataframe and rdd. Best fo both worlds.

paragraphs.text:
%md

## Streaming

Pre spark 2.0 . RDD is used for batch processing. DStreams (Decretised rdd) in streaming. Problem: different api, event time is time when event enters Spark itself.
Now we have structured streaming, 1 api both both, static and continues dataframes. So Batch, interactive and streamign queries are the same. And query api's can be used to check current runnign qieries, stop and start etc.

paragraphs.title: Create structured stream input
paragraphs.text:
import org.apache.spark.sql.types._ 
import org.apache.spark.sql.functions._ 
import scala.concurrent.duration._ 
import org.apache.spark.sql.streaming.ProcessingTime 
import org.apache.spark.sql.streaming.OutputMode.Complete 

val michelSchema = new StructType().add("name", StringType).add("function", StringType).add("salary", LongType)
val streamingInputDF = spark.readStream.format("csv").schema(michelSchema).option("header", false).option("inferSchema", true).option("sep", ",").option("maxFilesPerTrigger", 1).load("CsvFiles")

%md

## Install mysql

Log in your Docker image:
docker exec -it 9ac9fdfa5d12 bash

Install and test Mysql, as our docker image is a Debian Ubuntu image we use these steps:
apt-get update
apt-get dist-upgrade
apt-get install mysql-server mysql-client
<use password for Root, example: michel, enter it twice>

/etc/init.d/mysql start
mysql -u root -p
<Enter the password>

Follow these steps to configure zeppelin jdbc interpreter  to use mysql:
https://zeppelin.apache.org/docs/0.7.0/interpreter/jdbc.html

THIS IS PROBABLY NOT NEEDED:
wget https://dev.mysql.com/get/Downloads/Connector-J/mysql-connector-java-5.1.44.zip
unzip mysql-connector-java-5.1.44.zip
cp /usr/zeppelin/mysql-connector-java-5.1.44/mysql-connector-java-5.1.44-bin.jar /usr/zeppelin/lib
export ZEPPELIN_CLASSPATH="/usr/zeppelin/lib"
/usr/zeppelin/bin/zeppelin.sh restart

import org.apache.spark.{SparkConf, SparkContext}
import org.apache.spark.sql.{SparkSession, DataFrame}

def readExcel(file: String): DataFrame = spark.read.
  format("com.crealytics.spark.excel").
  option("path", file).
  option("useHeader", "true").
  option("treatEmptyValuesAsNulls", "true").
  option("inferSchema", "true").
  option("addColorColumns", "False").
  load()
  
val retailDF = readExcel("Online Retail.xlsx")
z.show(retailDF)

paragraphs.title: Spark Interpreter has a Sql option in Zeppelin
paragraphs.text:
%sql

select InvoiceNo,count(*) from retail group by InvoiceNo order by count(*) desc

paragraphs.title: Alternatively create RDD , add schema for Dataframe creation, and add extra timestamp column
paragraphs.text:
import org.apache.spark.sql.types._
import org.apache.spark.sql.Row
import org.apache.spark.sql.types.{StructType,StructField}

val inFileRDD = sc.textFile("retail.csv")
val allRowsRDD = inFileRDD.map(line  =>line.split(";").map(_.trim))
val header = allRowsRDD.first
val data = allRowsRDD.filter(_(0) != header(0))
val fields = Seq( StructField("pandaId",IntegerType,true),
  | StructField("invoiceNo", StringType, true),
  | StructField("stockCode", StringType, true),
  | StructField("description", StringType, true),
  | StructField("quantity", IntegerType, true),
  | StructField("invoiceDate", StringType, true),
  | StructField("unitPrice", DoubleType, true),
  | StructField("customerID", StringType, true),
  | StructField("country", StringType, true)
  | )
//Creating schema can be done multiple ways)
val schema = StructType(fields)
val rowRDD = data.map(attributes => Row(attributes(0).toInt, attributes(1), attributes(2), attributes(3), attributes(4).toInt, attributes(5), attributes(6).toDouble, attributes(7),attributes(8)))

val r1DF = spark.createDataFrame(rowRDD, schema)
val ts = unix_timestamp($"invoiceDate","yyy-MM-dd HH:mm").cast("timestamp")
val r2DF = r1DF.withColumn("ts", ts)
val selectData = r2DF.select("invoiceNo", "stockCode", 
      "description", "quantity", "unitPrice", "customerID", "country", 
      "ts")
val writeData = selectData.withColumnRenamed("ts", 
      "invoiceDate")
      

z.show(writeData)

paragraphs.title: Write into Mysql
paragraphs.text:
//Spark needs the mysql driver in its classpath, so in spark interpreter within zeppelin config enu make sure you add the mysql driver as dependency
import java.util.Properties

val dbUrl = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/retailDB"
val prop = new Properties()
prop.setProperty("user", "root")
prop.setProperty("password", "michel")
writeData.write.mode("append").jdbc(dbUrl, "transactions", prop)

paragraphs.title: Create external table ddl script!
paragraphs.text:
val tablename="piet"
val path ="/usr/zeppelin/spark-warehouse/piet" //Use hdfs://bla if using hdfs
val rawSchema = sqlContext.read.parquet(path).schema
val schemaString = rawSchema.fields.map(field => field.name.replaceAll("""^_""", "").concat(" ").concat(field.dataType.typeName match {
        case "integer" => "int"
        case smt => smt
      })).mkString(",\n")

      val ddl =
      s"""
         |Create external table $tablename ($schemaString) \n
         |partitioned by (y int, m int, d int, hh int, mm int) \n
         |Stored As Avro \n
         |-- inputformat 'org.apache.hadoop.hive.ql.io.avro.AvroContainerInputFormat' \n
         | -- outputformat 'org.apache.hadoop.hive.ql.io.avro.AvroContainerOutputFormat' \n
         | Location 'hdfs://$path'
       """.stripMargin
z.show(ddl)

paragraphs.title: Using mongo within Spark
paragraphs.text:
%md

In zeppelin added dependency within spark interpreter: org.mongodb.spark:mongo-spark-connector_2.11:2.1.0 , hoping it will get the jars from:
http://repo1.maven.org/maven2/org/mongodb/spark/mongo-spark-connector_2.11/2.1.0/

Install mongo db on docker image:
docker exec -it 9ac9fdfa5d12 bash

In bash:
apt-key adv --keyserver hkp://keyserver.ubuntu.com:80 --recv 0C49F3730359A14518585931BC711F9BA15703C6
echo "deb http://repo.mongodb.org/apt/debian jessie/mongodb-org/3.4 main" | tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/mongodb-org-3.4.list
apt-get update
apt-get install -y mongodb-org
mkdir /data
mkdir /data/db
mkdir /data/db/log
<needed? mongod --dbpath data/db --fork --logpath data/db/log>
mongod


In new shell on the docker image, start new bash and run a shell:
mongo
use micheldb;
db.movie.insert({"name":"tutorials point"})
show databases;
show collections;

paragraphs.title: Lets read our movie name from Mongo and print it
paragraphs.text:
import org.apache.spark.sql.SQLContext
import org.apache.spark.{SparkConf, SparkContext}
import com.mongodb.spark.MongoSpark
import com.mongodb.spark.config.{ReadConfig, WriteConfig}

val readConfig = ReadConfig(Map("uri" -> "mongodb://localhost:27017/micheldb.movie?readPreference=primaryPreferred"))
val writeConfig = WriteConfig(Map("uri" -> "mongodb://localhost:27017/micheldb.outCollection"))
case class Movie (name : String)
val movieDF = MongoSpark.load(sc, readConfig).toDF[Movie]

movieDF.take(1).foreach(println) //yeah it prints tutorials point
